{"url": "https://towardsdatascience.com/forecasting-total-number-of-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-india-using-autoregressive-forecast-2d56addca07a", "time": 1683006084.896488, "path": "towardsdatascience.com/forecasting-total-number-of-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-india-using-autoregressive-forecast-2d56addca07a/", "webpage": {"metadata": {"title": "Forecasting total number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in India using Autoregressive Forecast Model | by Nischal Madiraju | Towards Data Science", "h1": "Forecasting total number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 in India using Autoregressive Forecast Model", "description": "Note from the editors: Towards Data Science is a Medium publication primarily based on the study of data science and machine learning. We are not health professionals or epidemiologists, and the\u2026"}, "outgoing_paragraph_urls": [{"url": "http://towardsdatascience.com", "anchor_text": "Towards Data Science", "paragraph_index": 0}, {"url": "https://www.who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/situation-reports", "anchor_text": "here", "paragraph_index": 0}], "all_paragraphs": ["Note from the editors: Towards Data Science is a Medium publication primarily based on the study of data science and machine learning. We are not health professionals or epidemiologists, and the opinions of this article should not be interpreted as professional advice. To learn more about the coronavirus pandemic, you can click here.", "In continuation of my previous posts about COVID-19 data endpoints and their visualization, here is a quick way you can build a simple time series forecasting model: -", "For those who are not familiar with what time series forecasting is: A time series is a series of data points indexed (or listed or graphed) in time order. Most commonly, a time series is a sequence taken at successive equally spaced points in time. In a forecasting setting, we find ourselves at time t and we are interested in estimating Y(t+h), using only information available at time t.", "I have personally used the Autoregressive forecast model. An Autoregression is a time series model that uses observations from previous time steps as input to a regression equation to predict the value at the next time step. It is a very simple idea that can result in accurate forecasts on a range of time series problems.", "And then we fetch the required data from its respective endpoint accordingly and train the Autoregression model with it.", "Here for training, I have only used data till 17\u201304\u20132020 so that I can use it to predict the total number of confirmed cases on 18\u201304\u20132020 and compare it with the actual value.", "Now to predict the value of 18\u201304\u20132020 (i.e. the 87th value in the list of data hence the number 87 beside the predicted value) I have passed the start and end index parameters to the predict function as the total length of the input data as that will give the index of required prediction (i.e. if I have 87 values the index of last input value will be 86 and the value passed as start & end param would be 87, telling it to predict the 87th value).", "That gave me a prediction of approx. 15879 which is quite close to the real value of 15722", "While passing data for the Autoregression model index was passed as \u2018[\u2018Cases\u2019][:-1]\u2019 in order to only pass the confirmed cases column of the dataframe and the \u2018:-1\u2019 was used to skip the last value which was the value of the date 18\u201304\u20132020.", "When training a model you fit it, fitting a model means finding a pattern in data. That is why I had used model.fit() in the training process.", "Start and end params: These params are used to define how many values are to be predicted. In my example, I passed the same number for both of them since I wanted only one value to be predicted. But if you want to let us say predict the total confirmed cases for the next 4 days then in \u2018start\u2019 you will pass the index from which point of time the prediction is to be started and in \u2018end\u2019 you will pass till which point of time the value needs to be predicted i.e. since your list ended at 86 index you can either pass \u2018start\u2019 as 87 and \u2018end\u2019 as 90 statically or if you want to pass it dynamically in \u2018start\u2019 send the length of your data and then in \u2018end\u2019 pass total length + 3 which will give you the same result", "One thing to note about statsmodels AR() library is that it makes it difficult to use this in on \u2018online\u2019 fashion (e.g., train a model and then add new data points as they come in). You\u2019d need to either retrain your model based on the new datapoint added or just save the coefficients from the model and predict your own values as needed.", "You can find my code here:", "Feel free to go through it and also let me know in the comments if you would like me to cover anything else", "Your home for data science. A Medium publication sharing concepts, ideas and codes.", "Writes about Artificial intelligence, Machine Learning and Deep Learning. Pursuing Msc in Artificial Intelligence at the University of Groningnen"], "all_outgoing_urls": [{"url": "https://rsci.app.link/?%24canonical_url=https%3A%2F%2Fmedium.com%2Fp%2F2d56addca07a&%7Efeature=LoOpenInAppButton&%7Echannel=ShowPostUnderCollection&source=---two_column_layout_nav----------------------------------", "anchor_text": "Open in app"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=register&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fforecasting-total-number-of-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-india-using-autoregressive-forecast-2d56addca07a&source=post_page---two_column_layout_nav-----------------------global_nav-----------", "anchor_text": "Sign up"}, {"url": "https://medium.com/m/signin?operation=login&redirect=https%3A%2F%2Ftowardsdatascience.com%2Fforecasting-total-number-of-confirmed-cases-of-covid-19-in-india-using-autoregressive-forecast-2d56addca07a&source=p